Leveraged Credit Forecast Update: Moving the Goalpost: Growth indicators have been resilient with 3Q US GDP tracking above our economists' already upwardly revised estimate of \(1.5\%\) . As well, the Fed has been pulled forward with our economists now forecasting a 25bp cut at each of the next four meetings (Sept, Oct, Dec, Jan). The forecast adjustment by our economists away from an initial cut at the December meeting has also been driven by softer- than- expected inflation readings. Recently, Powell's Jackson Hole remarks confirmed market expectations for the FOMC to cut the funds rate by 25bp at its next meeting in mid- September. And away from Jackson Hole, the Fed has made headlines for a very different reason: the administration's efforts to reshape the Fed. For reference, OIS forwards are fully pricing in only two cuts cumulatively over the next four Fed meetings because of the strength of growth- related data (PMIs, Retail Sales). Meanwhile, 2Q was one of the strongest earnings season in years for HY companies with guidance also very strong in aggregate (High Yield Earnings Tracker). And with the lowest yields for leveraged credit issuers since 2022, HY/LL companies have accessed capital markets in droves with the past 3 months' refinancing in- line with 2024's record pace (\$56bn per month Jun- Aug). Recently, we raised our FY issuance forecasts with the window of opportunity for issuers expected to extend post Labor Day (Credit Strategy Weekly Update). Our 2025 new- issue forecasts (HY \$300bn/\$90bn, \$985bn/\$190bn) incorporate a very active capital market backdrop in September and into October, that said we do expect softer growth and firmer inflation data to raise market volatility and constrain activity as we progress through 4Q. But with the slowdown in growth and rise in inflation indicators incorporated in our economists' forecast taking longer to materialize, we use this opportunity to adjust our YE25 HY/LL spread, yield, and full- year return targets. Specifically, revise lower our YE25 high- yield bond and leveraged loan spread forecasts to 375bp (from 450bp) and 475bp (from 550bp), respectively. For high- yield bonds, this translates into a yield of \(7.5\%\) (+50bp versus now) and a FY25 total return of \(7.5\%\) (or \(1\%\) from now through YE25). This forecast incorporates a year- end 5- year Treasury yield of \(3.65\%\) (- 5bp). For leveraged loans, this translates into a \$- price of roughly \$96.0 and FY25 total return of approximately \(5.5\%\) (or \(1.5\%\) from now through YE25). This forecast incorporates a year- end 3- month SOFR rate of \(3.65\%\) (- 55bp). We still expect 50bp of spread widening as markets progress through 4Q as we do believe the full impact of tariffs on growth and inflation are yet to be fully reflected in business and consumer behavior. Despite a expected economic slowdown into early 1H26, we continue to believe leveraged credit spreads will remain inside their long- term average (25yr avg. HY/LL spread

550bp) due to solid balance sheets for most issuers, ample liquidity following a record refi wave, manageable default risk, attractive yields, and historically strong credit quality (HY). Additionally, leveraged credit investors are already defensively positioned. We continue to believe investors should maintain a defensive portfolio and recommend HY fund managers Overweight BBs, Neutral Single Bs and Underweight CCcs. We also recommend loan managers Overweight B1s or higher, Neutral B2s, and Underweight B3s or lower. We continue to forecast a 2025 default rate for high-yield bonds and leveraged loans of \(1.50\%\) and \(3.25\%\) , respectively.

--High-Yield and Leveraged Loan Market Brief: High-yield bond prices rose for a fifth straight session on Thursday \((+\) 0.07 d/d, \(+0.05\%\) HYG) alongside a \(+0.3\%\) gain in the S&P500 and a 3bp decline in 10yr Treasury yield amid a solid 2Q GDP revision and stable claims. Claims continue to provide a reasonably optimistic picture of the labor market, with initial claims down slightly from a year earlier and continuing claims holding in a narrow range since mid-June. Meanwhile, real 2Q GDP was revised up from \(3.0\%\) to \(3.3\%\) , while the core PCE deflator was revised down from \(2.54\%\) to \(2.47\%\) ; we still project the deflator rose \(2.9\%\) oya in July, but this slightly increases the risk of rounding down to \(2.8\%\) . High-yield bond yields and spreads declined 2bp apiece on Thursday to \(6.96\%\) and 323bp, respectively, which are

26bp lower and 2bp wider in August and are 63bp and 2bp lower year- to- date. Yields are below \(7\%\) for the first time since April 2022. BB- rated bonds (+0.11% d/d) outperformed Single Bs (+0.08% d/d) and CCCs (+0.08% d/d). And from a sector stance, Food/Bev. (+0.15% d/d) outperformed while Chemicals (+0.00% d/d) underperformed the HY indexes' +0.10% daily gain. By rating, BB bond yields are now 5.83% (-3bp d/d), B yields are 6.98% (-2bp d/d) and CCC yields are 11.20% (-2bp d/d). And BB spreads are now 210bp (-2bp d/d, +3bp August, -2bp YTD), B spreads are 327bp (-3bp d/d, +5bp August, +3bp YTD), and CCC spreads are 749bp (-2bp d/d, -1bp August, +67bp YTD). For reference, BB, B, and CCC spreads are now 23bp, 35bp, and 117bp off the pre- Liberation tights. HY/IG spreads of 244bp (-2bp d/d, +2bp YTD) are 9bp below their 12M average, while BBB/BB spreads of 111bp (-2bp d/d, +1bp YTD) are 1bp above their 12M average. High- yield bonds are providing a +1.26% gain in August with CCCs (+1.60%) outperforming BBs (+1.30%) and Single Bs (+1.13%). The HY index is providing a +6.57% gain year- to- date with CCCs (+6.99%) outperforming BBs (+6.79%) and Single Bs (+6.15%). Meanwhile, no deals priced yesterday which has August's issuance at \$25.7bn (\$9.8bn ex- refi) following \$37.5bn (\$8.3bn ex- refi) in July. Gross HY new- issue volume totaling \$208.7bn is now ahead of the \$203.1bn of volume priced over the same period last year (+3%), while net volume of \$58.5bn (ex- refi) YTD compares with \$44.3bn YTD24 (+32%).

Yesterday's attachment included a historical series of high- yield bonds currently callable or callable within one year and trading above or within \(1 of its call price (par, \%)\) . Also included is an industry breakdown and a list of each individual bond in this cohort today. The amount of high- yield bonds currently callable or callable within one year and trading above or within \(1 of its call price has risen to a 3.5yr high of\) 266bn (or 17.7% of the developed universe). This compares to as high as \(342bn at YE21. On a percentage basis, 17.7% compares to the long- term median and average of 6.9% and 8.3%, respectively. Notably, the avg. coupon on the\) 266bn of debt is 7.53%. And the largest industry contributors are Energy ( \(45bn or 28% of industry), Financial (\) 26bn or 18%), Industrials ( \(26bn or 34%) and Gaming/Leisure (\) 24bn or 22%). The five largest bonds are TIBX's \(3.8bn 9.0% of 29", DTV's \)3.7bn 5.875% of 27", DISH's \(3.5bn 11.75% of 27", HBGCN's \)3.3bn 7.25% of 30", and EMECLI's \(2.8bn 6.625% of 30".

In July 2025, \(74.4bn of leveraged loans traded per LSTA which was up +1\% m/m and up +16\% yoy. Notably, July's volume follows June's\) 73.7bn, May's \(79.0bn and April's second highest monthly loan volume on record (\$109.2bn). 2Q25 posted a record\) 261.9bn of loans traded which compares to 1Q25's \(254.2bn and a 10 - quarter average of\) 205.3bn. YTD loan trading volume of \(590.5bn is up +24\% y/y and compares to\) 477.1bn YTD24. For context, July has historically ranked as the fourth weakest trading month of the calendar year averaging \(49.6bn since 2007. For reference, the most active trading months for loans in 2024 were October (\$79.4bn), April (\$72.5bn), and May (\$72.5bn) with December and June (\$62.7bn) the lightest. And loan trading volume averages\) 84.4bn per month YTD compared to \(68.5bn and\) 59.6bn per month in 2024 and 2023, respectively. What is the monthly turnover rate for the leveraged loan asset class? We calculate the monthly turnover rate for leveraged loans in July as 4.90\%, compared to a monthly average 4.77\% in 2024 (or 57\% per annum). How does this compare to high- yield bonds? We calculate the monthly turnover rate for high- yield bonds at 14.79\% in July which follows 14.75\% in June, and compares to an average monthly rate of 13.62\% in 2024 (or 163\% per annum). What accounts for the differential? A few reasons loans trade less than bonds include the holder base for leveraged loans (heavy CLO, bank participation) and the inability to short which limits hedge fund participation. Lastly, the median bid- ask spread in July was 50bp according to LSTA versus 53bp in 2024, 75bp in 2023, 84bp in 2022, 48bp in 2021, 120bp in 2020, 67bp in 2019, 53bp in 2018, and 51bp in 2017. In other words, in pricing environments where the \% above Par is elevated (2021 and 2017/18) the bid- ask spread has tended to be narrower. Notably, July's BAS tightened 38bp since April's bid- ask spread (88bp) which was the widest since the regional banking crisis.

Tuesday's attachment included average gross and net new- issue volumes by calendar month since 2010 for high- yield bonds and institutional loans. Leveraged credit issuance has been above average in August with loans posting a record August issuance. Since 2010, September has been the most active month for HY averaging \(33.6bn\) of volume (or \(33\%\) above avg.). The next most active months on a gross basis are May ( \(31.9bn\) ) and March ( \(31.8bn\) ), whereas the two least active months are December ( \(15.0bn\) ) and August ( \(19.4bn\) ). And on a non- refi related basis, the three most active months for HY are September ( \(14.4bn\) ), April ( \(12.0bn\) ), and May ( \(12.0bn\) ). For Loans, the three most active months on a gross basis are February ( \(58.6bn\) ), January ( \(56.3bn\) ), and June ( \(51.2bn\) ). And the two least active are August ( \(31.3bn\) ) and September ( \(37.8bn\) ). On a non- refi/repricing basis, October ( \(20.6bn\) ) has been the most active for loans.
